 🚀 Step-by-Step Migration Strategy

  1. Assess the current application

Start with a full inventory:

Project types (Web API, MVC, Worker, Class libraries)
Dependencies (NuGet packages, third-party libs)
External integrations (DB, APIs, messaging)

👉 Key check:

Are all packages compatible with modern .NET?
2. Upgrade to a stable intermediate version (recommended)

Instead of jumping directly:

👉 Move:

3.1 → 6 (LTS) → 8 → 10

Why?

Smaller breaking changes
Easier debugging
Better support path

  3. Update project files (.csproj)

Convert old format if needed:

<TargetFramework>net10.0</TargetFramework>

Also:

Remove obsolete references
Ensure SDK-style projects

  4. Update NuGet packages
Upgrade all packages to latest compatible versions
Replace deprecated libraries

Examples:

Old logging → modern logging providers
Old auth libs → modern identity packages

👉 This is often the biggest blocker

  5. Handle breaking changes in ASP.NET Core
Key changes from 3.1:
❌ Old (Startup.cs pattern)
public class Startup
{
    public void ConfigureServices(IServiceCollection services) { }
    public void Configure(IApplicationBuilder app) { }
}
✅ New (minimal hosting model)
var builder = WebApplication.CreateBuilder(args);
var app = builder.Build();

app.MapControllers();
app.Run();

👉 You can:

Migrate fully
Or temporarily keep old style (supported but not recommended)


  6. Update middleware and routing

Changes to check:

Endpoint routing is now standard
Middleware ordering may need adjustment
Authentication/authorization config updated

  7. Update configuration handling
Move from Startup.cs to Program.cs
Use builder.Configuration

Also:

Validate appsettings structure
Update environment configs


  8. Modernize dependency injection
Built-in DI is more powerful now
Remove custom DI frameworks if unnecessary

  9. Update EF Core (if used)
Upgrade EF Core version step-by-step
Check:
LINQ query changes
Migrations compatibility

  dotnet ef migrations add UpgradeMigration

0. Fix obsolete APIs

Common issues:

Removed or renamed methods
Deprecated libraries
Behavior changes

👉 Use compiler warnings as your guide
Breaking changes in tracking/behavior


11. Introduce performance improvements (optional but valuable)

After migration:

Enable async everywhere
Use Minimal APIs where appropriate
Add caching (Redis, memory cache)
Optimize JSON serialization (System.Text.Json)



12. Update testing
Run all unit/integration tests
Fix broken tests due to:
Behavior changes
Dependency updates


13. Container & deployment updates

If using Docker:

Update base images:
FROM mcr.microsoft.com/dotnet/aspnet:10.0

Also:

Validate CI/CD pipelines
Update runtime environments
14. Validate performance & regression
Compare:
Response times
Memory usage
CPU utilization

👉 Ensure no regressions

15. Deploy in stages
Deploy to Dev → QA → Staging → Prod
Use:
Blue-green deployment
Feature flags
Canary releases
